Jim Yong Kim served as the 12th president of the World Bank Group. Soon after he assumed his position in July 2012, the organization established two goals to guide its work: to end extreme poverty by 2030 and to boost shared prosperity, focusing on the bottom 40 percent of the population in developing countries. In September 2016, the World Bank Group Board unanimously reappointed Kim to a second five-year term as president. In early 2019, Kim resigned from the World Bank to join a firm focused on infrastructure investments.

During his first term, the World Bank Group supported the development priorities of countries at levels never seen outside a financial crisis and, with its partners, achieved two successive, record replenishments of the World Bank Group’s fund for the poorest. The institution also launched several innovative financial instruments, including facilities to address infrastructure needs, prevent pandemics and help the millions of people forcibly displaced from their homes by climate shocks, conflict, and violence.

Kim's career has revolved around health, education and delivering services to the poor. In 1987, he co-founded Partners In Health, a nonprofit medical organization that works in poor communities on four continents. He has received a MacArthur "genius" grant, was recognized as one of America's "25 Best Leaders" by U.S. News & World Report and was named one of TIME magazine's "100 Most Influential People in the World.

title: Doesn't everyone deserve a chance at a good life?

aws-transcripts.transcript: I just want to share with you what I have been experiencing over the last five years and having the great privilege of traveling to many of the poorest countries in the world. This scene is one I see all the time everywhere, and these young children are looking at a smartphone, and the smartphone is having a huge impact and even the poorest countries, I said to my team, You know, what I see is a rise of aspirations all over the world. In fact, it seems to me that there's a convergence of aspirations, and I asked a team of economists, actually look into this, you know, Is this true, our aspirations converging all around the world. So they looked at things like Gallup polls about satisfaction in life, and what they learned was that if you have access to the Internet, your satisfaction goes up. But another thing happens. That's very important. Your reference income, the income to which you compare your own also goes up. Now, if you're if the reference income of a nation, for example, goes up 10% by comparing themselves to the outside, then on average, people's own incomes have to go but least 5% to maintain the same level of satisfaction. But when you get down into the lower percentiles of income, your income has to go much more if the reference income goes up 10% something like 20%. And so, with this rise of aspirations, the fundamental question is Are we gonna have a situation where aspirations are linked, opportunity and you get dynamism and economic growth, like like that which happened in the country I was born in in Korea or our aspirations gonna meet frustration. This is a really concerned because between 2012 and 2015 terrorism incidents increased by 74%. The number of deaths from terrorism went up 150%. Right now, 2,000,000,000 people live in conditions of fragility, conflict, violence and by 2030 more than 60% of the world's poor will live in these situations of fragility, conflict and violence. And so what do we do about meeting these aspirations? Are there new ways of thinking about how we can rise to meet these aspirations? Because if we don't, I'm extremely worried. Aspirations, air rising as never before because of access to the Internet everyone knows how everyone else lives, has our ability to meet those aspirations risen as well. And just to get the details of this, I want to share with you my own personal story. This is not my mother, but in the During the Korean War, my mother literally took her own sister, her younger sister, on her back, and walked at least part of the way to escape Seoul during the Korean War. Now, through a series of miracles, my mother, father both got scholarships to go to New York City. They actually met in New York City and got married in New York City. My father, too, was a refugee at the age of 19. He left his family in the northern part of the country, escaped through the border and never saw his family again. Now, when they we're married and living in New York, My father was a waiter at Patricia Murphy's restaurant. Their aspirations went up. They understood what it was like to live in a place like New York City in the 19 fifties. Well, my brother was born and they came back to Korea, and I we had what I remember is kind of an idyllic life. But what was happening in Korea at that time was the country was one of the poorest in the world, and there was political upheaval. There were demonstrations just down the street from our house all the time, students, students protesting against the military government and, at the time, the aspirations of the World Bank group, the organization. I lied. Now we're extremely low for Korea. Their idea was that Korea would find it difficult without foreign aid to provide its people was more than the bare necessities of life. So the situation is Korea's in a tough position. My parents have seen what life is like in the United States that got married there. My brother was born there, and they felt that in order to give us an opportunity to reach their aspirations for us, we had to go and come back to the United States. Now we came back. First. We went to Dallas. My father did his dental degree all over again, and then we ended up moving toe Iowa, of all places. We grew up in Iowa and Iowa. We went through the whole course. I went toe, I went to high school. I went to college and then one day, uh, very something that I'll never forget. My father picked me up after my sophomore year in college, and he was driving me home and he said, Jim, what are your aspirations? What do you want to study? What do you want to do?
